      <hedline>
        <hl1>Corrections</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Correction of July 20 article: Nassau County jail guard who won suit contending he was harassed for being gay was not protected by any federal, state or county ban on discrimination based on sexual orientation, but 17 other New York municipalities have such laws</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>An article last Thursday about a Nassau County jail guard who won a lawsuit contending that he was harassed for being gay misstated his reason for filing under the equal protection clause of the 14th Amendment to the Constitution. No federal, state or Nassau County law prohibits discrimination based on sexual orientation. But such laws indeed exist in some jurisdictions in the state: 17 other municipalities, including 10 counties, have them.</p>
      </block>
